{"author":{"id":"144ad87499f23e542ca19f06c7fd2eff0a1056f0f72b792d2cb236eca4d75d06"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1535691252,"nonce":"415Rr1kB3DB1RN1RLi3rnaNzxy0=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUzNTU4Mzg3Mzg=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/2057","origin":"github"},"title":"scRNA-Seq Workflows","message":"This issue is a place to discuss how to create and collaborate on flexible scRNA-Seq workflows. \n\nI've tried to collate the main points of the discussion that started [here](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/pull/2047). \n\nFeel free to edit!\n\nping @bgruening @mtekman @blankenberg @pcm32 @pinin4fjords\n\n**Intermediate format(s)**\n- Would be really good to decide on an \"exchange\" format. This is important to enable interaction between methods of different tools.\n- Some HDF5 dialect like the loom format could be nice to explore - http://linnarssonlab.org/loompy/ and https://satijalab.org/loomR/loomR_tutorial.html.\n- Could then have e.g. a scNormalisation tool in Galaxy that offers all different normalization methods that the Python and R community comes up with and we simply consume and write loom files\n- This should go inside the bioconda package as well\n- It's a complex issue and I can see it providing quite a few challenges, so a community-driven solution would be really awesome.\n\n**Structure of tools**\n- Separate by functionality e.g. Filtering, Normalisation, Confounder Removal, and Clustering, similiar to what was previously proposed here https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/pull/1841\n- Avoid putting all functionalities together because then you cannot cherry pick the different functionalities from the different tools and used them together (ie. use filtering from seurat with normalization from sc3 and clustering from scanpy, to name an example).\n- Could create one sc-filtering tool, one sc-normalization tool\n- The Galaxy tool could call the appropriate script from the relevant *-scripts bioconda package.\n- Should have a reasonable editorial effort in deciding what is shown in the end in Galaxy, as there will be functionality that might be unnecessary to add (maybe internal methods). Having too many methods per tool will confuse users.\n\n**Creating wrappers**\n- Could make wrappers either with R2G2, Rscript2Galaxy, manually, or a combination\n- Should build upon the r-seurat-scripts, r-scater-scripts. \n- Should add the R scripts to the bioconda -scripts package instead of having them right next to the Galaxy wrapper, so that the work can be re-used in a similar way on other workflow environments.\n- We need to see whether auto-generated wrappers are adequate in terms of usability, we might find that we are better off with 5, 10 or 15 modules for Seurat that are manually written but focus on core functionality and are truly useful for users, instead of several tenths that are difficult to understand.\n- Could try to harness the power given by r2g2 to produce scripts that we can add to the bioconda packages, but then work on top of that to trim to relevant functions and cherry pick Galaxy wrappers for important functionality instead of just any method available inside.","files":null}]}